109
00:06:05,565 --> 00:06:07,900
 narrator: pecans grow on trees 

110
00:06:07,902 --> 00:06:10,635
       that are native to       
  south central north america.  

111
00:06:10,637 --> 00:06:13,238
       in fact, "pecan" is      
        an algonquin word       

112
00:06:13,240 --> 00:06:16,374
  that means "a nut that takes  
       a stone to crack."       

113
00:06:16,376 --> 00:06:21,246
  today, computerized shelling  
  machines do that job for you. 

114
00:06:21,248 --> 00:06:23,182
                     ♪♪         

115
00:06:23,184 --> 00:06:26,585
        pecans add flavor       
    and crunch to any recipe.   

116
00:06:26,587 --> 00:06:30,122
  they can also be a satisfying 
       treat on their own.      

117
00:06:30,124 --> 00:06:34,927
 but manufacturing pecans is an 
entirely different nut to crack.

118
00:06:36,263 --> 00:06:41,066
 at harvest time, the husks that
 contain the nuts start to open.

119
00:06:41,068 --> 00:06:42,601
        at this orchard,        

120
00:06:42,603 --> 00:06:44,469
 a machine grabs the tree trunks

121
00:06:44,471 --> 00:06:47,339
       and shakes the nuts      
         to the ground.         

122
00:06:47,341 --> 00:06:53,879
                     ♪♪         

123
00:06:53,881 --> 00:06:57,416
       once on the ground,      
   a sweeper moves the pecans   

124
00:06:57,418 --> 00:07:00,486
       away from the trees      
         and into a row.        

125
00:07:00,488 --> 00:07:03,621
       it also blows away       
   some of the lighter debris.  

126
00:07:03,623 --> 00:07:06,025
                     ♪♪         

127
00:07:06,027 --> 00:07:11,163
 a harvester with paddle wheels 
      collects the pecans.      

128
00:07:11,165 --> 00:07:14,900
     once on the harvester,     
 the pecans ride chain conveyors

129
00:07:14,902 --> 00:07:18,170
        as vacuums remove       
       and discard debris       

130
00:07:18,172 --> 00:07:23,776
 then the pecans are transferred
      to a cleaning plant.      

131
00:07:23,778 --> 00:07:26,779
     the pecans are unloaded    
           into a pit,          

132
00:07:26,781 --> 00:07:30,916
         and a conveyor         
       takes them inside.       

133
00:07:30,918 --> 00:07:35,387
the pecans funnel into a slotted
     drum and tumble around.    

134
00:07:35,389 --> 00:07:38,323
         the drum sorts         
       the dehusked pecans      

135
00:07:38,325 --> 00:07:41,326
  from those that have retained 
          their husks.          

136
00:07:41,328 --> 00:07:43,195
    in this enclosed machine,   

137
00:07:43,197 --> 00:07:47,265
      spinning wire brushes     
    remove more of the husks.   

138
00:07:47,267 --> 00:07:50,269
   blowers release the lighter  
      husks into a big bin      

139
00:07:50,271 --> 00:07:53,005
    to be disposed of later.    

140
00:07:53,007 --> 00:07:54,673
     after more processing,     

141
00:07:54,675 --> 00:07:59,211
      pictures of the nuts      
     are taken with cameras.    

142
00:07:59,213 --> 00:08:01,480
       a computer monitors      
          the pictures          

143
00:08:01,482 --> 00:08:05,484
          for any husks         
  still attached to the pecans. 

144
00:08:05,486 --> 00:08:07,085
     if any are identified,     

145
00:08:07,087 --> 00:08:11,090
     the computer activates     
    a blower to remove them.    

146
00:08:13,293 --> 00:08:16,628
     with the husks removed,    
       harvesters sort out      

147
00:08:16,630 --> 00:08:20,265
     any of the pecans that     
   are cracked or split open.   

148
00:08:22,636 --> 00:08:27,106
    at this point, the pecans   
  contains about 12% moisture,  

149
00:08:27,108 --> 00:08:30,842
      which is high enough      
     to cause deterioration.    

150
00:08:30,844 --> 00:08:34,913
 so harvesters leave the pecans 
      to dry for 24 hours,      

151
00:08:34,915 --> 00:08:38,384
 to lower their moisture content
             to 4%.             

152
00:08:38,386 --> 00:08:40,319
    once drying is complete,    

153
00:08:40,321 --> 00:08:43,255
   the pecans are transferred   
     to the shelling plant,     

154
00:08:43,257 --> 00:08:46,458
   where they are plunged into  
   a chlorine-and-water bath.   

155
00:08:46,460 --> 00:08:49,461
      this both cleans them     
      and rehydrates them.      

156
00:08:49,463 --> 00:08:51,329
  without sufficient moisture,  

157
00:08:51,331 --> 00:08:54,399
 the pecans will break into bits
        during cracking,        

158
00:08:54,401 --> 00:08:59,471
 and the objective is to extract
    intact halves for retail.   

159
00:08:59,473 --> 00:09:01,273
 the pecans are rinsed in water 

160
00:09:01,275 --> 00:09:04,275
        at a temperature        
   of 180 degrees fahrenheit.   

161
00:09:04,277 --> 00:09:06,945
            this step           
    removes chlorine residue,   

162
00:09:06,947 --> 00:09:09,147
      sanitizes the pecans,     

163
00:09:09,149 --> 00:09:13,685
 and raises the moisture content
            to 7.5%.            

164
00:09:13,687 --> 00:09:15,487
  now it's time to get cracking 

165
00:09:15,489 --> 00:09:19,358
       with the completely      
       automated process.       

166
00:09:19,360 --> 00:09:20,692
       inside the sheller,      

167
00:09:20,694 --> 00:09:24,029
      pistons hit each end      
    of a nut simultaneously,    

168
00:09:24,031 --> 00:09:25,831
      cracking it cleanly.      

169
00:09:25,833 --> 00:09:29,768
   the deshelled pecans travel  
    across a vibrating sifter   

170
00:09:29,770 --> 00:09:32,371
    that sorts them by size.    

171
00:09:32,373 --> 00:09:36,108
  then the pecans fall in front 
    of an electronic system,    

172
00:09:36,110 --> 00:09:38,377
  which releases a blast of air 

173
00:09:38,379 --> 00:09:41,246
   that removes any lingering   
          shell pieces.         

174
00:09:41,248 --> 00:09:42,915
     a second sifting system    

175
00:09:42,917 --> 00:09:46,185
     removes any additional     
        small pecan bits.       

176
00:09:46,187 --> 00:09:48,120
 these pecans will be processed 

177
00:09:48,122 --> 00:09:51,790
         into candy bars        
    and commercial pastries.    

178
00:09:51,792 --> 00:09:55,026
      the electronic sorter     
 has removed most of the shells,

179
00:09:55,028 --> 00:09:56,595
      but not all of them.      

180
00:09:56,597 --> 00:09:59,331
    technicians visually scan   
           the pecans           

181
00:09:59,333 --> 00:10:03,669
          and pick out          
      the remaining shells.     

182
00:10:03,671 --> 00:10:06,538
    the pecans continue along   
          the conveyor          

183
00:10:06,540 --> 00:10:10,943
  and fall into cardboard boxes 
     at the end of the line.    

184
00:10:10,945 --> 00:10:13,411
           to prepare           
   a toasted pecan snack food,  

185
00:10:13,413 --> 00:10:16,081
    salt and butter are added   
          to the nuts.          

186
00:10:16,083 --> 00:10:19,618
    then the nuts are cooked    
     and mixed in a roaster.    

187
00:10:21,355 --> 00:10:25,090
    in packaging, technicians   
         pour the pecans        

188
00:10:25,092 --> 00:10:26,624
      into measuring jugs,      

189
00:10:26,626 --> 00:10:29,694
         then empty them        
       into plastic bags.       

190
00:10:29,696 --> 00:10:33,232
                     ♪♪         

191
00:10:33,234 --> 00:10:36,234
          hot jaws seal         
      the tops of the bags      

192
00:10:36,236 --> 00:10:41,306
    to keep the pecans fresh    
  and extend their shelf life.  

193
00:10:41,308 --> 00:10:45,176
   ready for retail, consumers  
     won't have any trouble     

194
00:10:45,178 --> 00:10:46,711
     cracking these pecans.     

195
00:10:46,713 --> 00:10:49,448
      they can go straight      
          to snacking.          

196
00:10:49,450 --> 00:10:51,450
                     ♪♪         

197
00:10:59,260 --> 00:11:03,995
                     ♪♪         

198
00:11:03,997 --> 00:11:06,265
            narrator:           
    a belt and pulley system    

199
00:11:06,267 --> 00:11:08,333
  is a simple type of machine.  

200
00:11:08,335 --> 00:11:10,135
   two or more pulleys rotate,  

201
00:11:10,137 --> 00:11:12,037
          moving a belt         
      wrapped around them,      

202
00:11:12,039 --> 00:11:14,673
          transferring          
        mechanical power.       

203
00:11:14,675 --> 00:11:18,076
    torque, speed, direction,   
        and other factors       

204
00:11:18,078 --> 00:11:19,878
 can be altered by using pulleys

205
00:11:19,880 --> 00:11:23,415
      of varying diameters      
          and designs.          

206
00:11:23,417 --> 00:11:25,350
                     ♪♪         

207
00:11:25,352 --> 00:11:27,218
   split pulleys drive a belt,  

208
00:11:27,220 --> 00:11:29,554
       while idler pulleys      
          apply tension         

209
00:11:29,556 --> 00:11:32,423
    or change its direction.    

210
00:11:32,425 --> 00:11:35,027
      both are manufactured     
        from steel coil,        

211
00:11:35,029 --> 00:11:36,895
  the industrial term for steel 

212
00:11:36,897 --> 00:11:40,832
        that's delivered        
    to the factory in a roll.   

213
00:11:40,834 --> 00:11:43,368
     the width and thickness    
      of the steel varies,      

214
00:11:43,370 --> 00:11:46,170
      depending on the size     
    of the pulley being made    

215
00:11:46,172 --> 00:11:48,040
   and the load it will carry.  

216
00:11:48,042 --> 00:11:50,041
                     ♪♪         

217
00:11:50,043 --> 00:11:54,178
 to make split pulleys, the coil
    enters a stamping press,    

218
00:11:54,180 --> 00:11:56,315
    which punches out discs.    

219
00:11:56,317 --> 00:12:00,385
   each disc, called a blank,   
     will become one pulley.    

220
00:12:00,387 --> 00:12:04,322
   the scrap pieces go back to  
 the steel mill to be recycled. 

221
00:12:04,324 --> 00:12:07,326
      each blank has a hole     
         in the center.         

222
00:12:07,328 --> 00:12:11,196
      this particular blank     
     has three drain holes.     

223
00:12:12,466 --> 00:12:15,734
     a magnetic arm picks up    
       one blank at a time      

224
00:12:15,736 --> 00:12:19,404
        and loads it into       
 an automated splitting machine.

225
00:12:21,275 --> 00:12:23,008
      as the blank rotates,     

226
00:12:23,010 --> 00:12:26,077
a circular knife cuts the border
        around the blank        

227
00:12:26,079 --> 00:12:27,612
      to a specific depth,      

228
00:12:27,614 --> 00:12:29,848
splitting the edge of the blank.

229
00:12:29,850 --> 00:12:33,885
  on the opposite side, another 
  tool spreads the split edge,  

230
00:12:33,887 --> 00:12:35,220
        forming a groove.       

231
00:12:35,222 --> 00:12:37,689
       the machine doesn't      
        remove any steel.       

232
00:12:37,691 --> 00:12:41,293
   rather, it forms the groove  
       to a specific shape      

233
00:12:41,295 --> 00:12:45,163
        by redistributing       
       the existing metal.      

234
00:12:45,165 --> 00:12:49,967
a welder places the split pulley
     into a welding machine,    

235
00:12:49,969 --> 00:12:54,373
     then inserts a machined    
  steel hub in the center hole. 

236
00:12:54,375 --> 00:12:58,977
  the machine welds the hub to  
 the pulley in about 20 seconds.

237
00:13:00,247 --> 00:13:03,314
     an idler pulley is made    
         from two halves        

238
00:13:03,316 --> 00:13:07,252
 rather than from a single blank
     like the split pulley.     

239
00:13:07,254 --> 00:13:11,390
  to make each half, the steel  
    coil goes through a press   

240
00:13:11,392 --> 00:13:14,126
         in which a dye         
     with multiple stations     

241
00:13:14,128 --> 00:13:16,794
        stamps the metal        
     to the required shape,     

242
00:13:16,796 --> 00:13:19,030
   then cuts it from the coil.  

243
00:13:19,032 --> 00:13:21,466
                     ♪♪         

244
00:13:21,468 --> 00:13:24,336
       separate conveyors       
   feed the two stamped halves  

245
00:13:24,338 --> 00:13:26,471
    to an assembly carousel.    

246
00:13:26,473 --> 00:13:28,807
            one half            
   runs through a small press   

247
00:13:28,809 --> 00:13:31,676
      which stamps dimples      
         on the surface,        

248
00:13:31,678 --> 00:13:37,415
       then loads it onto       
  the carousel's first station. 

249
00:13:37,417 --> 00:13:40,886
    the carousel then rotates   
      to the next station,      

250
00:13:40,888 --> 00:13:45,690
     which inserts a radial     
ball bearing in the center hole.

251
00:13:45,692 --> 00:13:50,162
 the next station places a stamp
        without dimples.        

252
00:13:50,164 --> 00:13:52,831
        a press squeezes        
       the parts together       

253
00:13:52,833 --> 00:13:57,702
     until the dimples touch    
      the non-dimpled half.     

254
00:13:57,704 --> 00:14:00,906
    a magnetic arm transfers    
     the pulley to a track,     

255
00:14:00,908 --> 00:14:02,774
 leading to a projection welder.

256
00:14:02,776 --> 00:14:06,043
 the welder applies an electric 
     current to the dimples,    

257
00:14:06,045 --> 00:14:10,515
     melting the two halves     
 together at the contact points.

258
00:14:10,517 --> 00:14:13,985
     a robotic arm positions    
 the pulley on the next station,

259
00:14:13,987 --> 00:14:17,923
  which presses a bore adapter  
 into the center of the bearing.

260
00:14:17,925 --> 00:14:21,059
 this adapter enables the pulley
         to be installed        

261
00:14:21,061 --> 00:14:22,994
      with a smaller bolt.      

262
00:14:22,996 --> 00:14:26,598
    the thickness of the bore   
  adapter also acts as a spacer 

263
00:14:26,600 --> 00:14:31,269
     to align the center of     
 the pulley with the belt path. 

264
00:14:31,271 --> 00:14:34,739
  next, the samples are tested  
       for weld strength.       

265
00:14:34,741 --> 00:14:38,009
     a hydraulic jaw clamps     
     one half of the pulley     

266
00:14:38,011 --> 00:14:41,213
     while another jaw pulls    
      the other half apart.     

267
00:14:41,215 --> 00:14:45,149
  the welds must remain intact  
        to pass the test.       

268
00:14:45,151 --> 00:14:49,087
  split pulleys undergo a weld  
    strength test on the hub.   

269
00:14:49,089 --> 00:14:52,690
   a hot chemical bath removes  
    traces of lubricating oil   

270
00:14:52,692 --> 00:14:55,760
left by the machining equipment.

271
00:14:55,762 --> 00:14:58,964
      a thorough rinse with     
    an anticorrosion chemical   

272
00:14:58,966 --> 00:15:01,099
 prevents the steel from rusting

273
00:15:01,101 --> 00:15:04,969
      and preps the surface     
          for painting.         

274
00:15:04,971 --> 00:15:07,105
    once the pulleys are dry,   

275
00:15:07,107 --> 00:15:09,774
     a technician loads them    
      onto the paint line,      

276
00:15:09,776 --> 00:15:12,043
 masking the center with a plug.

277
00:15:12,045 --> 00:15:16,915
                     ♪♪         

278
00:15:16,917 --> 00:15:19,651
      inside the automated      
          paint tunnel,         

279
00:15:19,653 --> 00:15:21,520
   three spray guns fully coat  

280
00:15:21,522 --> 00:15:24,523
   the top, middle, and bottom  
     of the spinning pulley     

281
00:15:24,525 --> 00:15:27,191
with a water-based enamel paint.

282
00:15:27,193 --> 00:15:30,462
                     ♪♪         

283
00:15:30,464 --> 00:15:33,264
         then the pulley        
  passes through a tunnel oven, 

284
00:15:33,266 --> 00:15:36,535
   which heat cures the paint   
     in about four minutes.     

285
00:15:36,537 --> 00:15:40,404
                     ♪♪         

286
00:15:40,406 --> 00:15:43,074
           the pulley,          
     upon exiting the oven,     

287
00:15:43,076 --> 00:15:45,944
          goes directly         
     into the shipping box,     

288
00:15:45,946 --> 00:15:51,282
     and an unpainted pulley    
  takes its place on the line.  

289
00:15:51,284 --> 00:15:54,753
the factory sends select pulleys
     to an outside facility     

290
00:15:54,755 --> 00:15:57,889
     to be plated with zinc     
      rather than painted.      

291
00:15:57,891 --> 00:16:00,625
       zinc plating better      
       protects the steel       

292
00:16:00,627 --> 00:16:03,862
         when exposed to        
     corrosive environments.    

293
00:16:11,972 --> 00:16:16,842
                     ♪♪         

294
00:16:16,844 --> 00:16:19,577
      narrator: looking for     
     a new pair of glasses?     

295
00:16:19,579 --> 00:16:21,446
      if so, you might want     
          to look into          

296
00:16:21,448 --> 00:16:24,982
      durable, lightweight,     
  and flexible acetate frames.  

297
00:16:24,984 --> 00:16:27,519
           acetate is           
     a high-quality plastic     

298
00:16:27,521 --> 00:16:29,788
made from cotton or wood fibers.

299
00:16:29,790 --> 00:16:32,857
      it can be produced in     
   an endless array of colors,  

300
00:16:32,859 --> 00:16:35,627
       color combinations,      
          and finishes.         

301
00:16:37,397 --> 00:16:40,598
         this eyewear is        
   made of cellulose acetate,   

302
00:16:40,600 --> 00:16:43,668
      a transparent plastic     
     made from cotton fibers    

303
00:16:43,670 --> 00:16:48,273
   combined with plasticizers   
          and binders.          

304
00:16:48,275 --> 00:16:51,209
       the acetate arrives      
        as a thick sheet.       

305
00:16:51,211 --> 00:16:53,277
     a computer-guided mill     
           cuts a slab          

306
00:16:53,279 --> 00:16:57,715
   for the front of the frame   
 and two pieces for the temples.

307
00:16:57,717 --> 00:16:59,951
     the cuts are carefully     
           calculated           

308
00:16:59,953 --> 00:17:01,786
 to ensure any color variations 

309
00:17:01,788 --> 00:17:06,090
       will be in the same      
    location on every frame.    

310
00:17:06,092 --> 00:17:08,759
       this machine heats       
      the frame front slab      

311
00:17:08,761 --> 00:17:11,496
       and applies a mold       
    to form the bridge bump,    

312
00:17:11,498 --> 00:17:15,566
      the part of the frame     
 that bulges out over the nose. 

313
00:17:15,568 --> 00:17:19,504
   the machine drops the slab   
        into cold water.        

314
00:17:19,506 --> 00:17:23,375
    once the slab has cooled,   
  this computer-guided machine  

315
00:17:23,377 --> 00:17:26,044
  shapes it into a frame front. 

316
00:17:26,046 --> 00:17:27,846
    using 16 different tools    

317
00:17:27,848 --> 00:17:30,448
         operating from         
     five different angles,     

318
00:17:30,450 --> 00:17:32,450
     the machine carves out     
          the eyeholes          

319
00:17:32,452 --> 00:17:35,387
    and makes grooves in them   
       to hold the lenses,      

320
00:17:35,389 --> 00:17:38,189
  then carves the outer shape.  

321
00:17:38,191 --> 00:17:40,725
  an artisan refines the shape  

322
00:17:40,727 --> 00:17:43,061
          and smoothes          
      the surface by hand,      

323
00:17:43,063 --> 00:17:46,664
           using files          
     and custom-made tools.     

324
00:17:46,666 --> 00:17:50,401
     then the acetate parts     
     are placed in a tumbler    

325
00:17:50,403 --> 00:17:53,805
       with hardwood pegs       
    and polishing compounds.    

326
00:17:53,807 --> 00:17:58,743
     the acetate is smoothed    
and polished by gentle abrasion.

327
00:17:58,745 --> 00:18:02,614
   a tiny pocket is carved on   
  each side of the frame front  

328
00:18:02,616 --> 00:18:04,548
         for the hinge.         

329
00:18:04,550 --> 00:18:08,887
   next, the machine heats the  
 hinge with an electric current 

330
00:18:08,889 --> 00:18:10,956
  and places it in the pocket.  

331
00:18:10,958 --> 00:18:15,493
   the heat melts the acetate,  
   securely setting the hinge.  

332
00:18:17,230 --> 00:18:21,833
     the brand logo features    
 a pyramid comprised of 21 dots.

333
00:18:21,835 --> 00:18:24,302
      this computer-guided      
      precision drill bores     

334
00:18:24,304 --> 00:18:28,106
          21 tiny holes         
   into the tip of the temple.  

335
00:18:28,108 --> 00:18:32,777
     a craftsman fills them     
     with translucent epoxy.    

336
00:18:32,779 --> 00:18:34,845
      once the epoxy dries,     

337
00:18:34,847 --> 00:18:39,650
the craftsman removes the excess
 epoxy with a fine sanding disc.

338
00:18:39,652 --> 00:18:43,188
   this requires applying just  
 the correct amount of pressure.

339
00:18:43,190 --> 00:18:46,257
     otherwise, the acetate     
        can get damaged.        

340
00:18:46,259 --> 00:18:48,994
    custom-designed equipment   
       tapers each temple       

341
00:18:48,996 --> 00:18:50,795
     to an ergonomic shape.     

342
00:18:50,797 --> 00:18:54,265
      the temple is thicker     
   at the hinge for strength,   

343
00:18:54,267 --> 00:18:57,068
     thinner around the back    
     of the ear for comfort,    

344
00:18:57,070 --> 00:19:00,338
    and thickest at the end,    
   creating weight at the back  

345
00:19:00,340 --> 00:19:04,209
       to offset pressure       
   on the bridge of the nose.   

346
00:19:04,211 --> 00:19:06,744
        next, a craftsman       
        heats the temple        

347
00:19:06,746 --> 00:19:08,913
     to soften the acetate.     

348
00:19:08,915 --> 00:19:12,349
    the temple is loaded into   
    a wire-shooting machine,    

349
00:19:12,351 --> 00:19:16,087
       along with a hinged      
       nickel silver wire.      

350
00:19:16,089 --> 00:19:19,757
   the machine shoots the wire  
 through the core of the temple.

351
00:19:19,759 --> 00:19:22,160
  the temple is now adjustable  

352
00:19:22,162 --> 00:19:25,830
         and attachable         
    to the frame front hinge.   

353
00:19:25,832 --> 00:19:29,267
           a craftsman          
carefully removes excess acetate

354
00:19:29,269 --> 00:19:31,369
       with a razor blade.      

355
00:19:31,371 --> 00:19:33,971
                     ♪♪         

356
00:19:33,973 --> 00:19:37,509
then he smoothes out the acetate
        around the hinge        

357
00:19:37,511 --> 00:19:39,310
       with a heat press.       

358
00:19:39,312 --> 00:19:43,047
  finally, he covers the hinge  
        with a glue cap.        

359
00:19:43,049 --> 00:19:44,982
 this will shield it from damage

360
00:19:44,984 --> 00:19:48,186
    throughout the remainder    
   of the production process.   

361
00:19:48,188 --> 00:19:52,256
                     ♪♪         

362
00:19:52,258 --> 00:19:55,059
   a laser engraves the logo,   
           model name,          

363
00:19:55,061 --> 00:19:59,197
   color, and size information  
  on the inside of the temple.  

364
00:19:59,199 --> 00:20:02,267
    now the glasses are ready   
        to be assembled.        

365
00:20:02,269 --> 00:20:06,805
a craftsman cuts matching angles
 on the temples and frame front.

366
00:20:06,807 --> 00:20:09,207
                     ♪♪         

367
00:20:09,209 --> 00:20:11,743
       he joins the temple      
     and frame front hinges     

368
00:20:11,745 --> 00:20:14,078
   with a nylon-coated screw.   

369
00:20:14,080 --> 00:20:16,481
           the coating          
   tightens the parts together  

370
00:20:16,483 --> 00:20:19,851
      and helps the temples     
    fold and unfold smoothly.   

371
00:20:20,954 --> 00:20:23,821
     a craftsman hand files     
           the angles           

372
00:20:23,823 --> 00:20:29,294
    so there's no gap between   
    temples and frame front.    

373
00:20:29,296 --> 00:20:31,496
   each frame is hand-polished  

374
00:20:31,498 --> 00:20:33,965
    with progressively finer    
         buffing wheels         

375
00:20:33,967 --> 00:20:37,035
          and different         
      polishing compounds.      

376
00:20:38,705 --> 00:20:43,307
 optical frames are shipped out 
 with temporary plastic lenses, 

377
00:20:43,309 --> 00:20:45,042
   which an optician replaces   

378
00:20:45,044 --> 00:20:48,246
       with the customer's      
      prescription lenses.      

379
00:20:48,248 --> 00:20:51,716
  this mechanical machine cuts  
    the plastic to the shape    

380
00:20:51,718 --> 00:20:55,453
    of the frame's eyeholes,    
     following a model lens.    

381
00:20:57,123 --> 00:21:00,525
    the temporary lenses have   
     a bevel on their edge,     

382
00:21:00,527 --> 00:21:03,260
         which fits into        
  the lens groove of the frame. 

383
00:21:03,262 --> 00:21:05,129
      from start to finish,     

384
00:21:05,131 --> 00:21:08,933
  it takes two weeks to create  
    a single pair of frames.    

385
00:21:08,935 --> 00:21:12,804
     the process takes over     
 70 different production steps, 

386
00:21:12,806 --> 00:21:15,974
     more than half of which    
     are performed manually.    

